distinct quadruplets (a, b, c, d) such that:\n\nnums[a] + nums[b] + nums[c] == nums[d], and\na < b < c < d\n\n \nExample 1:\n\nInput: nums = [1,2,3,6]\nOutput: 1\nExplanation: The only quadruplet that satisfies the requirement is (0, 1, 2, 3) because 1 + 2 + 3 == 6.\n\nExample 2:\n\nInput: nums = [3,3,6,4,5]\nOutput: 0\nExplanation: There are no such quadruplets in [3,3,6,4,5].\n\nExample 3:\n\nInput: nums = [1,1,1,3,5]\nOutput: 4\nExplanation: The 4 quadruplets that satisfy the requirement are:\n- (0, 1, 2, 3): 1 + 1 + 1 == 3\n- (0, 1, 3, 4): 1 + 1 + 3 == 5\n- (0, 2, 3, 4): 1 + 1 + 3 == 5\n- (1, 2, 3, 4): 1 + 1 + 3 == 5\n\n \nConstraints:\n\n4 <= nums.length <= 50\n1 <= nums[i] <= 100\n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def countQuadruplets(self, nums: List[int]) -> int:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass Solution:\n    def countQuadruplets(self, nums: List[int]) -> int:\n        n = len(nums)\n        count = 0\n        # Iterate over all possible quadruplets\n        for a in range(n):\n            for b in range(a + 1, n):\n                for c in range(b + 1, n):\n                    for d in range(c + 1, n):\n                        if nums[a] + nums[b] + nums[c] == nums[d]:\n                            count += 1\n        return count\n```\n\nThis solution iterates through all possible combinations of quadruplets `(a, b, c, d)` where `a < b < c < d` and checks if the condition `nums[a] + nums[b] + nums[c] == nums[d]` is satisfied. If it is, it increments the count. The constraints are small enough (with `nums.length` up to 50) that this brute-force approach will run efficiently.", "estimated_date": 1630800000000}